The '''Bahá'í Faith in Ethiopia''' began after [[`Abdu'l-Bahá]] wrote letters encouraging taking the religion to Africa in 1916.<ref name="ToDP8">{{cite book |author = `Abdu'l-Bahá |authorlink = `Abdu'l-Bahá |year = 1991 |title = Tablets of the Divine Plan |edition = Paperback |publisher = Bahá'í Publishing Trust |location = Wilmette, IL |isbn = 0-87743-233-3 |url =http://reference.bahai.org/en/t/ab/TDP/tdp-8.html.iso8859-1 | pages = 47–59 |origyear = 1916-17}}</ref> Probably the first Bahá'í to settle in the country came in early 1934<ref name="1st">{{cite magazine| title = INTERNATIONAL NEWS; From Circular Letter issued by the Spiritual Assembly of Haifa, June, 1934|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1934 | issue = 86 |pages=5–6 | url =}}</ref> and with further pioneers by mid-1934,<ref name="2nd">{{cite magazine| title = Baha'i Activities in Abyssinia|magazine= Bahá'í News |date=January 1935 | issue = 89 | page =7 | url =}}</ref> the first Bahá'í [[Local Spiritual Assembly]] of the country was elected in November in [[Addis Ababa]].<ref name="info">{{cite web| last = Hassall | first = Graham | title = Ethiopia | work = Research notes | publisher = Asia Pacific Bahá'í Studies | url = http://bahai-library.com/asia-pacific/country%20files/ethiopia.htm | doi =| accessdate = 2008-12-21}}</ref> In 1962, Ethiopia Bahá'ís had elected a [[National Spiritual Assembly]].<ref name="telegram">{{cite book |editor-last= Rabbani |editor-first=Ruhiyyih |year= 1992 |title= The Ministry of the Custodians 1957-1963 |publisher= Bahá'í World Centre |page = 398 |id= {{ISBN|0-85398-350-X}} |url= http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ministry_custodians |editor-link=Rúhíyyih Khanum |isbn= 0-85398-350-X }}</ref> By 1963 there were seven localities with smaller groups of Bahá'ís in the country.<ref name="stats">{{cite web | url =http://bahai-library.com/handscause_statistics_1953-63&chapter=1 | title = The Bahá'í Faith: 1844-1963: Information Statistical and Comparative, Including the Achievements of the Ten Year International Bahá'í Teaching & Consolidation Plan 1953-1963| others = Compiled by [[Hands of the Cause]] Residing in the Holy Land | pages = 28, 55}}</ref> The [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] estimated some 27000 Bahá'ís in 2005.<ref name="WCE-05">{{cite web| title = Most Baha'i Nations (2005) | work = QuickLists > Compare Nations > Religions > | publisher = The Association of Religion Data Archives | year = 2005| url =http://www.thearda.com/QuickLists/QuickList_40c.asp | accessdate = 2009-07-04}}</ref> The community celebrated its diamond jubilee in January 2009.<ref name="program">{{cite web
