The Bahá'í Community in Ethiopia came under the responsibility of the regional National Spiritual Assembly of Egypt and Sudan during the [[Ten Year Crusade]] in 1953.<ref name="stats" /> This was during a period of wide scale growth in the religion across [[Sub-Saharan Africa]] near the end of the period of [[Colonisation of Africa]].<ref name="UofC">{{cite web|title=Overview Of World Religions |work=General Essay on the Religions of Sub-Saharan Africa |publisher=Division of Religion and Philosophy, [[University of Cumbria]] |url=http://philtar.ucsm.ac.uk/encyclopedia/sub/geness.html |accessdate=2008-04-16 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071209082606/http://philtar.ucsm.ac.uk/encyclopedia/sub/geness.html |archivedate=2007-12-09 }}</ref> [[Pioneering (Bahá'í)|Pioneers]] continued to arrive like Fred Schechter in 1954<ref>{{cite magazine| title = World Crusade; Fifth Pioneer report |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1954 | issue = 277 | page =5 | url =}}</ref> and Dr. Amín'u'lláh Misbáh who lived there from 1955-1959.<ref name="xviii" /> [[Bahá'í Holy Days#Holy days|Bahá'í Holy days]] and [[Bahá'í Marriage]] certificates were recognized in Addis Ababa, and the assembly obtained legal incorporation in 1955-56. The community subsequently became part of the regional National Assembly of North-East Africa in 1956. A summer school in 1958 was held in Eritrea, then part of Ethiopia, hosting a significant expansion of the effort which included Bahá'ís from several cities: Addis Ababa, Gondar, Adiqualla, Massawa, Agordat, Barentu, and Asmara. The program included a variety of subjects: "Baha'i Administration" by Charles Hassan of Addis Ababa, "Baha'i History" by Dr. Hushang Ahdieh of Asmara, "Islam" by Mrs. Jeanne Mesbah of Asmara, "The Laws and Ordinances of Baha'u'llah" by Dr. Farhoumand, and "Meditatinn" by Dr. Walter Niederreiter.<ref name="WorldCrusade1959">{{cite magazine| title = World Crusade; Fifth Pioneer report |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1959 | issue = 336 | page =8 | url =}}</ref> The Bahá'ís were allowed to send official observers to the first session of the Economic Commission for Africa of the United Nations held in Addis Ababa in late 1958: Gila Bahta and Charles Hassan of Addis Ababa, and [[Ali Nakhjavani]] of Kampala.<ref name="WorldCrusade1959" /> They succeeded in meeting and discussing the religion with representatives to the Commission and discussing a variety of issues including the [[Persecution of Bahá'ís]] in Iran.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Baha'i United Nations Observers Attend Economic Commission in Ethiopia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1959 | issue = 336 |pages=3–4 | url =}}</ref> The first Bahá'í summer school in Addis Ababa was held in May 1959 and included an observance of the ''12th Day'' of [[Ridván]]. The average attendance during the school sessions was twenty-five, and included many Bahá'ís of Addis Ababa and their non-Bahá'í friends.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Baha'is of Three Countries Attend First Addis Ababa Summer School |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=October 1959 | issue = 344 | page =6 | url =}}</ref> In 1960 a group of sixty-five, half of them guests of the Baha'is shown considerable interest in an introductory talk on the religion in Addis Ababa in the [[Amharic]] language.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = New Interest in Faith in Northeast Africa Despite Condemnation bv Eritrea Church |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1960 | issue = 348 | page =4 | url =}}</ref> In 1961 events began to multiply - members of the religion reached the towns of Volisso, [[Bedele]] and [[Shashamane]],<ref>{{cite magazine| title = International News Briefs |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1961 | issue = 360 | page =8 | url =}}</ref> participated in the dedication of the [[Bahá'í House of Worship]] in Uganda.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Hand of Cause 'Amatu'I-Baha Ruhiyyih Khanum Dedicates Mother Temple of Africa |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1961 | issue = 361 |pages=2–8 | url =}}</ref> and the assembly of Addis Ababa oversaw the first Bahá'í marriage.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = International News Briefs |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1961 | issue = 366 | page =9 | url =}}</ref> [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Enoch Olinga]] travelled extensively in East Africa in 1962 including Ethiopia<ref name="xviii" /> by which time Ethiopia Bahá'ís had elected a [[National Spiritual Assembly]].<ref name="telegram" /> The same year a Bahá'í Ethiopian student studying in Germany was elected president of the non-partisan Ethiopian Student Union.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Ethiopian Baha'i Student Honored in Germany |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1962 | issue = 378 | page =17 | url =}}</ref> By 1963 in addition to the assembly in Addis Ababa there were seven communities with smaller groups of Bahá'ís in [[Adwa|Adua]], [[Alemaya]], [[Debre Zeyit]], [[Dessie]], [[Dire Dawa]], [[Gondar]] & [[Jimma]] and twelve isolated members in other communities.<ref name="info" /><ref name="stats" /> And also in 1963 in a step of recognition of the religion the city government of Addis Ababa allocated land for use as a Bahá'í burial ground.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Burial Ground Acquired in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=May 1963 | issue = 378 | page =4 | url =}}</ref>

=== Regional organization ===

The Sudan/Egypt regional National Assembly existed until 1953 when it became a regional assembly for North East Africa. This included French Somaliland; Egypt, Sudan, Abyssinia, Libya, Eritrea, British Somaliland; Italian Somaliland; and Socotra Is.<ref>{{cite web | last =Hassall | first = Graham | title = This note concerns references to Africa in the Bahá'í Writings | work = Asian/Pacific Collection | publisher = Asia Pacific Bahá'í Studies | date = 2003-08-26 | url =http://bahai-library.com/asia-pacific/country%20files/africa.htm | accessdate = 2009-10-26}}</ref> The regional assembly was again re-organized when the institutions of the religion were made illegal in Egypt in 1960<ref name="us_dos_egypt">{{cite web | title = Egypt: International Religious Freedom Report | date = 2004-09-15 | author = U.S. Department of State | publisher = Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor | url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2004/35496.htm | accessdate = 2006-10-20| archiveurl= http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20061017184916/http%3A//www%2Estate%2Egov/g/drl/rls/irf/2004/35496%2Ehtm| archivedate= October 17, 2006 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> and again when Sudan, Somalia and Ethiopia formed their own regional assembly in 1968 with members: Gila Michael Bahta, Dr. Leo Neiderreitter, Gamal Rushdy, Asfaw Tessema, Dr. Heshmat Farhoumand, Dr. Hushang Ahdieh, Ursula Samandari, Assefaw Habte Michael and Rabbi Teele Mariam.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Bahá'í News Beliefs |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1966 | issue = 426 | page =15 | url =}}</ref> From 1968 into 69 there were a number of initiatives undertaken<ref name="68a">{{cite magazine| title = International News Briefs |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1969 | issue = 426 | page =6 | url =}}</ref> including reaching to outlying areas, international speakers<ref>{{cite magazine| title = International News Briefs; Ethiopia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1969 | issue = 456 | page =8 | url =}}</ref> and a winter school.<ref name="68a" />

==== Visit of Hand of the Cause Rúhíyyih Khanum ====

From 1969 to 1973 [[Hand of the Cause]] [[Rúhíyyih Khanum]] travelled through many countries including Ethiopia.<ref>{{cite web | editor = Greg Watson | others = Compiled by Greg Watson | author = | title = transcript of talks given by Mr. Nakhjavani and his wife | work = Informal Talks by Notable Figures | publisher = Bahai-library.com | year = 2001 | url = http://bahai-library.com/nakhjavani_talks_africa | doi = | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> She arrived in Ethiopia October 15 and spent a month touring the Bahá'í communities with coverage by print and, for the first time in Ethiopia radio, news outlets on her arrival.<ref name="tour">{{cite magazine| title = 'Amatu'l-Bahá Ruhyyih Khanum tours Tanzania, Kenya, Ethiopia; (sections devoted to Ethiopia) |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1969 | issue = 456 |pages=9–11 | url =}}</ref> She was received by [[Haile Selassie I of Ethiopia]] the same day.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | authorlink = Bahá'í International Community | title = Madame Rúhíyyih Rabbáni, leading Bahá'í dignitary, passes away in Haifa | journal = One Country | volume = 11 | issue = 04 | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | location = | date = March 2000 | url = http://www.onecountry.org/e114/e11401as_Rabbani_passing.htm | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> In the half-hour interview she communicated how she had long admired him because of the way he had conducted himself in the face of the many trials and hardships of his life, and by the way he had overcome them. Selassie gave her a gold medal from his Coronation.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nakhjavani | first = Violette | title = The Great African Safari - The travels of RúhíyyihKhánum in Africa, 1969-73 | publisher = George Ronald Publisher Ltd. | pages = 27–32 | url = https://docs.google.com/View?docid=dgshgd2h_927d2fc8wds | isbn = 978-0-85398-456-6}}</ref> In the days afterwards she was escorted by civic authorities to [[Genet, Ethiopia|Genet]] where a regional conference was held, in part to celebrate the Bahá'í holy day of the [[Birth of the Báb]], and dedicated the Banáni Teaching Institute. Villagers surprised the guests with a dance they had not shared previously and sung Bahá'í songs with English words - a language foreign to them - with clarity enough to be understood. At a stop in another village a couple local Muslim leaders converted to the religion in her presence.<ref name="tour" /> On return to Addis Ababa Rúhíyyih Khanum and some Ethiopian Bahá'ís were received by [[Princess Tenagnework]] Worke Haile Selassie and her daughter Princess [[Seble Desta]]. The following day the Bahá'í community sponsored an observance of [[United Nations Day]] with a public lecture by a member of the United Nations Secretariat stationed in Ethiopia, prefaced by remarks by Rúhíyyih Khanum who was able to first present the Bahá'í attitude toward, and relationship with, the United Nations.<ref name="tour2">{{cite magazine| title = 'Amatu'l-Bahá Ruhyyih Khanum tours Tanzania, Kenya, Ethiopia; Part II (sections devoted to Ethiopia) |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1970 | issue = 456 |pages=1–7 | url =}}</ref> The following day she flew to the [[Harari Region|Province of Harrari]] where she was received by the provincial governor, though she fell ill and a member of the national assembly flew her to [[Assab]] to recoup. Then in Eritrea she addressed audiences of government servants, school principals and teachers, and a women's organization on topics of science and religion, the place of a religious morality and the civilizing role of women, often with questions from the audiences often late into the night. Later, in discussion with Prince [[Asrate Medhin Kassa]] it became known that while in exhile some years earlier he had borrowed and read a copy of [[Bahá'u'lláh and the New Era]] in Amharic that had been given to the Emperor.<ref name="tour2" /> Rúhíyyih Khanum then toured ancient sites of Ethiopia, [[Axum]] and [[Lalibela, Ethiopia|Lalibela]]. Then she went to Gondar where Bahá'ís had recently been attacked and then detained in circumstances soon implicating a local priest. The uproar over the event was such that another priest and several others converted to the religion.<ref name="tour2" /> On return to Addis Ababa the Israeli Ambassador held a formal dinner in her honor. The next three nights she spoke to Bahá'í audiences and then celebrated the Bahá'í holy day of the [[Birth of Bahá'u'lláh]] and the trip to see the Bahá'ís of [[Sebeta]]. On the last return to Addis Ababa Crown Prince [[Amha Selassie of Ethiopia|Asfaw Wossen]] received her then she resumed her tour of Africa by going next to Kenya.<ref name="tour2" />

== Modern community ==

Since its inception the religion has had involvement in [[socio-economic development]] beginning by giving greater freedom to women,<ref name="iranhistory">{{cite web | last = Momen | first = Moojan | title = History of the Baha'i Faith in Iran | work = draft "A Short Encyclopedia of the Baha'i Faith" | publisher = Bahai-library.com | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_encyclopedia_iran#9.%20Social%20and%20economic%20development | accessdate = 2009-10-16}}</ref> promulgating the promotion of female education as a priority concern.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Kingdon | first = Geeta Gandhi | title = Education of women and socio-economic development | journal = Baha'i Studies Review | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | year = 1997 | url =http://bahai-library.com/kingdon_education_women_development }}</ref> That involvement was given practical expression by creating schools, agricultural coops, and clinics even then.<ref name="iranhistory" /> In 1970 representatives from seven National Spiritual Assemblies in Africa and from the [[Bahá'í International Community]] were the largest delegation to the first African Conference of Non-Governmental Organizations held in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. Of the 104 Non-Governmental Organization delegates and observers attending - representing seventy-four organizations from twenty countries in Africa- ten were Baha'is; and two Bahá'í representatives were the only participants from Mauritius and Swaziland. With background work in New York, preparatory work in Addis Ababa, and large participation by Bahá'ís, they received praise for their efforts and dependability by the NGO liaison representative of the Ethiopian government and by other UN personnel.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Baha'i International News Service; African Conference of Non-Governmental Organizations |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=August 1970 | issue = 473 | page =19 | url =}}</ref> A senior officer for the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa was the speaker at the gathering sponsored by the National Spiritual Assembly of North East Africa in Asmara late in 1973 to commemorate the 125th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. He spoke at length about the role of the Bahá'ís and like-minded organizations.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; Baha'is called dynamic force |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1974 | issue = 516 | page =1 | url =}}</ref> He repeated his sentiments in 1980.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; Ethiopia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=February 1981 | issue = 599 | page =14 | url =}}</ref> The religion entered a new phase of activity when a message of the [[Universal House of Justice]] dated 20 October 1983 was released.<ref>{{cite journal |title= The Baha'i Faith 1957–1988: A Survey of Contemporary Developments | first = Moojan | last = Momen |author2=Smith, Peter | year = 1989 | url = http://bahai-library.com/momen_smith_developments_1957-1988 |volume = 19 | journal = Religion |issue= 1 | pages=63–91 |doi= 10.1016/0048-721X(89)90077-8}}</ref> Bahá'ís were urged to seek out ways, compatible with the [[Bahá'í teachings]], in which they could become involved in the social and economic development of the communities in which they lived. Worldwide in 1979 there were 129 officially recognized Bahá'í socio-economic development projects. By 1987, the number of officially recognized development projects had increased to 1482.The modern Bahá'í community of Ethiopia has multiplied its interests internally and externally along these lines.

=== Growth ===

In 1969 there was one assembly in the [[Sidamo Province]] of south central Ethiopia, 18 in 1972 and 59 in 1974.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; Ethiopians solve election problem |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1975 | issue = 473 |pages=16–17 | url =}}</ref> In 1975 a total of seventy Local Spiritual Assemblies formed. A cultural clash in choosing leadership happened under such quick growth. People of Sidamo were used to an open atmosphere when choosing their leaders and had difficulty adjusting to secret ballot as normal in [[Bahá'í administration#Elections|Bahá'í electoral process]]. Nevertheless, the elections went forward and materials and classes were held covering the issues though human resources were thin under such rapid growth. Observers concluded that in 1975 things had gone well. In 1978 the Nure community organized and managed a local conference, and believers from other villages chaired the sessions. Succeeding local conferences were to be held in villages of Mudane and Dereba.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; 50-plus at conference |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1978 | issue = 568 | page =17 | url =}}</ref> In northern Ethiopia fighting had broken out. At one meeting Bahá'ís were inundated by refugee neighbors in an apartment building from shots fired. When the police arrived the Bahá'ís were vindicated from fears of cooperation in the attack when the chief of police discovered Bahá'ís were involved. He summoned his aides to help the wounded, apologetically made a purely ceremonial inspection of the house, and let them go, explaining that there was no need to investigate the Bahá'ís, that he knew the Bahá'ís were not a source of danger and he entertained no doubts about them.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; How Baha'is react in time of war |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=December 1975 | issue = 537 | page =14 | url =}}</ref> There are other stories of activities of small groups of Bahá'ís.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; 10 teaching trips offered at meeting (and) How a child of 5 teaches the Cause |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1976 | issue = 540 | page =18 | url =}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Ethiopia |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=September 1982 | issue = 618 |issn=0195-9212 | page =16 | url =}}</ref> In 1976 the first Baha'i newsletter in the Amharic language began publication.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Around the World; Africa; Newsletter published in Amharic language |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=June 1976 | issue = 543 | page =8 | url =}}</ref> Sabri Elias, founder of the community in Ethiopia, and his wife, returned in 1977 for the national convention before flying on back to [[Djibouti]].<ref name="reaping" />

Forty-two Bahá'ís from Ethiopia attended a regional conference called for by the [[Universal House of Justice]] in 2008 held in Johannesburg.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | author-link = Bahá'í International Community | title = Big turnout for regional Baha’i conferences | newspaper = Bahá'í International News Service | date = 2008-11-11 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/668 | accessdate = 2009-08-30 }}</ref> The [[Bahá'í House of Worship#Wilmette.2C Illinois.2C U.S.|North American Temple]] Bahá'í choir went to Addis Ababa in January 2009 for the 75th anniversary of the Bahá'í Faith in Ethiopia and sang at [[Holy Trinity Cathedral (Addis Ababa)|Holy Trinity Cathedral]] of Ethiopia, the [[Ethiopian National Museum]] and the [[Ethiopian National Theatre]].<ref name="program" /><ref name="video" /><ref>{{cite press release | title = Bahá’í Choir of North America Sings at Diamond Jubilee in Ethiopia | publisher = National Spiritual Assembly of the Bahá'ís of the United States | year = 2009 | url = https://docs.google.com/View?docid=dgshgd2h_789fhnbsfc3 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> Members of the choir flew in from U.S., Canada, Australia and Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Saunders |first=Jeff |title=Macedonia resident travels to Ethiopia to sing |newspaper=The-News-Leader.com |date=2009-03-18 |url=http://www.the-news-leader.com/news/article/4547930 |accessdate=2009-08-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716221203/http://www.the-news-leader.com/news/article/4547930 |archivedate=2011-07-16 |df= }}</ref> Speakers at the diamond jubilee included [[Ali Nakhjavani]] and his wife Violette Nakhjavani.<ref name="program" />

=== International peace ===

In the 1990s a ''Racism Dance'' was translated by an Ethiopian Bahá'í Youth Workshop (see [[Oscar DeGruy]]) which addressed racial, national/ethnic prejudices and was used to talk about war between Eritrea and Ethiopia.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Dacey | first = Jessica | title = Around the world, Bahá'í youth workshops promote tolerance | journal = One Country | volume = 09 | issue = 02 | publisher = Bahá'í International Community | location = | date = November 1997 | url = http://www.onecountry.org/oc92/oc9204as.html | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | author = Universal House of Justice | title = Bahá'í Youth: "A New Kind of People" | journal = The Bahá'í World | volume = XXIII | publisher = Bahá'í World Centre | pages = 167–190 | year = 1996 | url = http://info.bahai.org/article-1-9-2-8.html}}</ref> There was a 2007 Ethiopian-Eritrean Bahá'í Conference held in the United States.<ref>{{cite web | last = Dr Squires | first = Phil | title = Ethiopian-Eritrean Baha'i Conference | year = 2007 | url = https://www.flickr.com/photos/philsquires/sets/72157600560416598/ | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref>

=== Education ===

Among the Bahá'í teachings is the importance of education. In 1980 the National Assembly of Auxiliary Board consulted on a project for the [[International Year of the Child]]. They developed the project "Ha Hu in Nine Days," which was designed to help an illiterate person learn the Amharic alphabet in only nine days. It was presented to UNESCO representative in Ethiopia and liaison officer for the UN Economic Commission for Africa followed by the Minister of Education and chairman of the National Commission for IYC. Each meeting had a reporter from the English-language newspaper, ''The Ethiopian Herald''.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The Baha'fcommunity earns praise for developing a new literacy aid |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=April 1980 | issue = 516 |pages=6–7 | url =}}</ref> An experimental garden was set up in [[Sidamo Province]] as a demonstration field in the compound of the regional center to train Bahá'í farmers in improved agricultural techniques.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = Number of projects growing rapidly |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=March 1986 | issue = 660 |issn=0195-9212 | page =3 | url =}}</ref> In 1989 a Bahá'í expert and businessman in using [[appropriate technology]] from Swaziland traveled through six southern and eastern African countries including Ethiopia training local people in the manufacture of several kinds of fence-making machines and other technologies in building, agriculture and water programs. The 10-day training courses were organized by the National Spiritual Assemblies in each of the six countries.<ref>{{cite magazine| title = The World; Swaziland |magazine= Bahá'í News |date=July 1989 | issue = 660 |issn=0195-9212 | page =15 | url =}}</ref> Dr. Fisseha Eshetu, the President of [[Unity University]], a [[Bahá'í inspired school]],<ref>{{cite web | last = Universal House of Justice | first = | authorlink = Universal House of Justice | title = Ridván Letter, 1999 | work = Ridvan Messages from the Universal House of Justice | publisher = Bahá'í Library Online | year = 1999 | url = http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ridvan_1999 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Universal House of Justice | first = | authorlink = Universal House of Justice | title = Ridván Letter, 2000 | work = Ridvan Messages from the Universal House of Justice | publisher = Bahá'í Library Online | year = 2000 | url = http://bahai-library.com/uhj_ridvan_2000 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> received a "Global Young Entrepreneur" award at the 7th World Summit of Young Entrepreneurs in 2000<ref>{{Cite news | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | author-link = Bahá'í International Community | title = President of Ethiopia's Unity College Named "Global Young Entrepreneur" | newspaper = Bahá'í International News Service | date = 2000-10-01 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/68 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> after founding the institution in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|title=Database of African Journalism Schools > Unity University College |work=Database of African Journalism Schools |publisher=[[UNESCO]] |url=http://www.unesco-ci.org/cgi-bin/asj/page.cgi?g=Detailed%2F9.html;d=1 |accessdate=2009-08-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728144032/http://www.unesco-ci.org/cgi-bin/asj/page.cgi?g=Detailed%2F9.html%3Bd%3D1 |archivedate=2011-07-28 |df= }}</ref> In 2001 Eshetu has taken positions on the development of the internet in Ethiopia.<ref>{{cite web | last = Kinde | first = Samuel | title = Internet in Ethiopia | work = Ethiopian Engineering Resources | publisher = Ethiopian Computing and Information Technology Association | date = February 2001 | url = http://www.ethiopians.com/Engineering/Internet_ET.htm | doi = | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> Unity University was the first private institution of higher education to open in Ethiopia, and as of 2001 the journalism program was the only university-level independent journalism program in the country.<ref>{{cite web | last = Prof. Heruy | first = Tegest | title = Unity College Professor Gets Vision for Future From Visit to Educator Meeting and University of Georgia | work = Cox Center Activities - Sept. 1, 2001 to August 31, 2002 | publisher = University of Georgia | url = http://www.grady.uga.edu/coxcenter/Activities/Act_2001_to_2002/Act0102_26.php| accessdate = 2010-10-15}}</ref> "Tsehai Loves Learning" is a television show of a hand puppet in the [[Amharic]] language.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | author-link = Bahá'í International Community | title = Ethiopian giraffe captures children's hearts | newspaper = Bahá'í World News Service | date = 2007-02-11 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/504 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> There are about 45 local children's classes being offered currently by Bahá'í communities in Ethiopia<ref>{{Cite news | last = Bahá'í International Community | first = | author-link = Bahá'í International Community | title = Raising a new generation | newspaper = Bahá'í International News Service | date = 2006-10-11 | url = http://news.bahai.org/story/486 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> - more prominent schools<ref name="video">{{cite web|last= |first= |title=Choir Trip to Ethiopia for Baha'i Diamond Jubilee |work= |publisher= |url=http://bahai-videos.com/Choir-Trip-to-Ethiopia-for-Baha-i-Diamond-Jubilee.html |doi= |accessdate=2009-08-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120226222246/http://bahai-videos.com/Choir-Trip-to-Ethiopia-for-Baha-i-Diamond-Jubilee.html |archivedate=2012-02-26 |df= }}</ref> are the School of the Nations of Ethiopia<ref>{{cite web | title = School of Nations - About Us | work = | publisher = School of Nations | url = http://www.schoolofnations.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=44&Itemid=53 | accessdate = 2009-08-30}}</ref> and One Planet International School.<ref>{{cite web|title=One Planet International School - About Us |work= |publisher=One Planet International School |url=http://oneplanetschool.com/aboutus |accessdate=2009-10-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312085753/http://www.oneplanetschool.com/aboutus |archivedate=2010-03-12 |df= }}</ref>

