The '''Heavenly Quran''' ({{Lang-ar|أمّ الکتاب|lit=mother of the Book|translit=umm al-kitāb}}<ref name=":0">Diane Morgan ''Essential Islam: A Comprehensive Guide to Belief and Practice'' ABC-CLIO 2010 {{ISBN|978-0-313-36025-1}} page 30</ref>), according to a common [[Islam]]ic belief, is a primordial version of the Quran, mentioned in [[Surah]] {{cite quran|43|4|s=ns|b=n}} and referred in Surah {{cite quran|85|22|s=ns|b=n}}, that resides in heaven, distinct from the earthly [[Quran]].<ref name="Cite quran|13|39|s=ns">{{cite quran|13|39|s=ns}}</ref><ref name="Cite quran|43|4|s=ns">{{cite quran|43|4|s=ns}}</ref> It is disputed whether the revealed Quran is a precise copy of the Heavenly Quran or an abridged version. Commonly, [[Injil]] and the Islamic notion of [[Tawrat|Torah]] are thought to be part of the Heavenly Quran.<ref name=":0" /><ref>Reza Aslan ''No God But God: The Origins, Evolution and Future of Islam'' Random House 2008 {{ISBN|978-1-407-00928-5}} page 99</ref>

