'''Saman Khuda''' ('''Saman Khoda''', '''Saman-khudat''') was an 8th-century [[Iran|Persian]] noble whose descendants (the House of Saman) later became rulers of Persia (the [[Samanid Empire]]). He was a [[Dehqan]] from the village of Saman in [[Balkh province]] in present-day northern [[Afghanistan]] (then part of Persia).<ref>[https://books.google.dk/books?id=mKpz_2CkoWEC&pg=PA162 Bosworth, Clifford Edmund. ''The New Islamic Dynasties: A Chronological and Genealogical Manual'' p. 162]</ref> In the early 8th century, he came to [[Merv]], seat of the [[Caliphate|Caliphal]] governor of [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]], [[Asad ibn 'Abd Allah al-Qasri]] (ruled 723-727). Saman was originally a [[Zoroastrianism|Zoroastrian]].<ref>[http://www.avesta.org/dhalla/history6.htm Dhalla, M. N. ''History of Zoroastrianism'' (1938) Part 6, Chapter XLIII]</ref> However, he was so impressed with the piety of Asad ibn 'Abd-Allah al-Qasri, the [[Caliphate|Caliphal]] governor of [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]], that he converted to [[Islam]].<ref>Mohammad Taher, ''Encyclopaedic Survey of Islamic Culture'', pg. 84</ref> He named his son [[Asad ibn Saman|Asad]], allegedly in the governor's honor.

Caliph [[al-Mamun]] (786-833) subsequently appointed Asad's four sons – Saman Khuda's grandsons – as governors of [[Samarkand]], [[Ferghana]], [[Shash]] and [[Ustrushana]], and [[Herat]] in recognition of their role in the suppression of a revolt.<ref name="ShamsKam">[http://www.transoxiana.org/0110/kamoliddin_bahram_chobin.html Shamsiddin Kamoliddin, "To the Question of the Origin of the Samanids", ''Transoxiana'' 10 (July 2005)].</ref> This began the House of Saman; Saman Khuda's great-grandson [[Isma'il ibn Ahmad]] (849-907) became Amir of [[Transoxiana]] and [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]].

Saman was a 4th or 5th generation descendant of [[Bahram Chobin]],<ref name="ShamsKam"/><ref>Narshaki (trans. R. N. Frye), ''History of Bukhara'', Pg 79</ref> a noble of the ancient [[House of Mihran]], who played an important role in the history of the later [[Sassanian Empire]].<ref>R. N. Frye, ''The Golden Age of Persia'', London: Butler & Tanner Ltd., 1996, p. 200.</ref>

